{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643228,"nonce":"zye51G5QYQYg2s93UP6A2uM5MeA=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\nThe phrase \"networks trained with adversarial perturbations\" in the Motivation section is ambiguous. In the Part 2 context, this does NOT refer to adversarial/minimax training (APT or population-based adversary). It refers to networks trained with PAI-ASF where perturbations (curl fields) are present during training at varying amplitudes (pert_std). The \"adversarial\" here is used in the loose sense of \"exposed to perturbations,\" not in the minimax game-theoretic sense.\n\nThe specific models this module is designed to analyze are PAI-ASF-trained models (any architecture: GRU or vRNN; any gating: additive or multiplicative) evaluated under curl field perturbations crossed with SISU levels. The module parameterizes over both training perturbation std and SISU level as comparison axes.\n\nIf this module is later applied to Part 2.5 minimax-trained models, the comparison would need to be updated to specify the adversary type (single vs pop5) and training method (standard backprop vs minimax).\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}